{"ANU": {"name": "Kai Xun Chan", "link": "https://researchers.anu.edu.au/researchers/chan-kx", "colleges": "College of Science", "email": "kai.chan@anu.edu.au", "phone": "02-61257702", "expertise": ["Plant Cell And Molecular Biology", "Cell Metabolism", "Proteomics And Intermolecular Interactions Excl. Medical Proteomics"], "interest": ["I am interested in understanding the process of how different components of a plant cell communicate with one another to coordinate responses to environmental challenges. Specifically, I am investigating the regulation of signals involved in retrograde communication between chloroplasts and mitochondria with the nucleus during oxidative stresses such as drought and high light stress. Understanding these processes may uncover mechanisms of stress perception in plant energy organelles and and the role of protein redox regulation in organelle signaling. An additional research aspect that I am interested in is the assimilation and partitioning of the key macronutrient sulfur during abiotic stress, since sulfur is required for the synthesis of various stress-responsive compounds and its consumption requires careful coordination within the plant."], "biography": "", "project": [], "publication": [{"title": "Evolution of chloroplast retrograde signaling facilitates green plant adaptation to land", "year": "2019", "source": "PNAS - Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences of the United States of America, vol. 116, no. 11, pp. 5015-5020", "authors": ["Zhao C", "Wang Y", "Kai Xun Chan"]}, {"title": "The arabidopsis SAL1-PAP pathway: A case study for integrating chloroplast retrograde, light and hormonal signaling in modulating plant growth and development?", "year": "2018", "source": "Frontiers in Plant Science, vol. 9, no. 1171, pp. 1-8", "authors": ["Phua S", "Yan D", "Kai Xun Chan"]}, {"title": "Sensing and signaling of oxidative stress in chloroplasts by inactivation of the SAL1 phosphoadenosine phosphatase", "year": "2016", "sourc